President Barack Obama has issued a proclamation declaring March 2, 2010, as Read Across America Day. This day is dedicated to promoting literacy and encouraging children to read. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of literacy in everyday life and highlights the role of parents and caregivers in fostering a love for reading in children. The proclamation also mentions the birthday of Theodor Seuss Geisel, commonly known as Dr. Seuss, and recognizes his contributions to children's literature. The President urges families to make reading a priority and encourages activities such as visiting libraries, playing word games, and reading together. The proclamation concludes by calling upon individuals and organizations to observe Read Across America Day through appropriate programs and activities.